05559nam a22010935i 9780520927971DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209279717 a10.1525/97805209279712doi  a(DE-B1597)520687  a(OCoLC)55741664  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBM755.W395bD48 2003eb 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a296.8/332/092aB2221 aDeutsch, Nathaniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Maiden of Ludmir :bA Jewish Holy Woman and Her World /cNathaniel Deutsch. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (329 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Ansky Visits Ludmir -- t1. A Dybbuk Trilogy, or How the Maiden of Ludmir Became a Literary Figure -- t2. Writing the Maiden -- t3. Afterlives: Remembering the Maiden -- t4. The Curse, the Cossacks, and the Messiah: Ludmir Before the Maiden -- t5. Birth and Childhood -- t6. Love and Death -- t7. The Maiden Possessed -- t8. False Male and Woman Rebbe? -- t9. The Witch-hunt in Ludmir -- t10. The Wedding and Its Aftermath -- t11. In the Holy Land -- tConclusion: Tracing the Maiden -- tAfterword: Journey to Ludmir -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHannah Rochel Verbermacher, a Hasidic holy woman known as the Maiden of Ludmir, was born in early-nineteenth-century Russia and became famous as the only woman in the three-hundred-year history of Hasidism to function as a rebbe—or charismatic leader—in her own right. Nathaniel Deutsch follows the traces left by the Maiden in both history and legend to fully explore her fascinating story for the first time. The Maiden of Ludmir offers powerful insights into the Jewish mystical tradition, into the Maiden’s place within it, and into the remarkable Jewish community of Ludmir. Her biography ultimately becomes a provocative meditation on the complex relationships between history and memory, Judaism and modernity. History first finds the Maiden in the eastern European town of Ludmir, venerated by her followers as a master of the Kabbalah, teacher, and visionary, and accused by her detractors of being possessed by a dybbuk, or evil spirit. Deutsch traces the Maiden’s steps from Ludmir to Ottoman Palestine, where she eventually immigrated and re-established herself as a holy woman. While the Maiden’s story—including her adamant refusal to marry—recalls the lives of holy women in other traditions, it also brings to light the largely unwritten history of early-modern Jewish women. To this day, her transgressive behavior, a challenge to traditional Jewish views of gender and sexuality, continues to inspire debate and, sometimes, censorship within the Jewish community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWomen rabbisvBiography. 0aZaddikotvBiography. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  abiography.  acharismatic leader.  acommunity.  aconversion.  adiaspora.  aeurope.  afeminism.  agender roles.  agender studies.  agender.  ahasidic.  ahasidism.  ahistorical women.  aholy women.  aimmigration.  ajewish feminism.  ajewish history.  ajewish mysticism.  ajewish women.  ajewish.  ajudaica.  ajudaism.  akabbalah.  aludmir.  amaiden of ludmir.  amaiden.  amarriage.  amartyr.  amigration.  amodernity.  amysticism.  anonfiction.  aottoman empire.  apalestine.  aprophecy.  arebbe.  areligion.  areligious leaders.  areligious women.  arussia.  asexuality.  avisions.  awomen and religion.  awomens issues.  ayiddishkeit.08iTit